g.text: Hackathon 3
Day 1
Step 1: Choose Your Marketplace Type
My marketplace type would be General E-Commerce.
Step 2: Define Your Business Goals
* What problem does your marketplace aim to solve?
My marketplace would solve "OUT OF STOCK" problem and would work on timely product availability.
Maintaining a high sense of responsibility, we will make sure to provide items which a customer needs
on urgent.
* Who is your target audience?
Our target audience would be men who needs their essentials such as clothing, footwear, office supplies, etc. ;
women who needs grocery items, clothing, beauty products, etc. ; and students who are eager to shop their
favorite school supplies, study materials, textbooks and notebooks.
* What products or services will you offer?
We will offer students' essentials, health and fitness items, Home Items, Books and study materials, Sports
and outdoor gear, beauty products and office supplies.
* What will set your marketplace apart (e.g., speed, affordability, customization)?
We will focus on affordability as it is the major problem nowadays; quality to provide best of best of items;
Customization for basically students to customize their study materials and school supplies.
Step 3: Create a Data Schema
> ENTITIES:
1) Products (ID, name, price, stock, category, tags)
2) Orders (Order ID, Customer info, Product Details, Status, Timestamp)
3) Customers (Customer ID, name, contact info, Address, order history)
4) Delivery Zones (Zone name, coverage area, assigned drivers)
5) Shipment (Shipment ID, Order ID, Status, Delivery Date)

> ENTITIES IN MY MARKETPLACE:
1) Products:
ID: Unique identifier for each product.
Name: Name of the product.
Price: Cost per unit.
Stock: Quantity available.
Category: Product classification (e.g., Student Essentials, Tech Products, etc.).
Tags: Keywords for search (e.g., "New Arrival", "Discounted", etc.).
2) Orders:
Order ID: Unique identifier for each order.
Customer Info: Name, contact details, and delivery address.
Product Details: List of products, quantities, and prices.
Status: Order status (e.g., Pending, Shipped, Delivered).
Timestamp: Date and time when the order is placed.
3) Customers:
Customer ID: Unique identifier for each customer.
Name: Full name of the customer.
Contact Info: Phone number and email address.
Address: Delivery address for orders.
Order History: List of past orders placed by the customer.
4) Delivery Zones:
Zone Name: Name or identifier of the delivery zone.
Coverage Area: List of cities or postal codes served by this zone.
Assigned Drivers: Details of the drivers or couriers who service the zone.
5) Shipment:
Shipment ID: Unique identifier for shipment tracking.
Order ID: Linked order ID.
Status: Shipment status (e.g., In Transit, Delivered).
Delivery Date: Expected or actual delivery date.
